cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SI, cs.CY 

This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with the challenge of recommending diverse niche objects to users based on their past preferences. It also involves the use of algorithms to predict future likes and interests of users. 

It could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it involves the development of a new algorithm to address the diversity-accuracy dilemma of recommender systems. 

The Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is also a likely fit as the paper deals with the use of data and algorithms to make predictions about user preferences. 

The Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category is another possible fit as the paper deals with recommending objects based on user or object similarity. 

Finally, the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category is a less likely fit, but still possible as the paper deals with the challenge of making accurate and diverse recommendations without relying on any semantic or context-specific information, which could have implications for privacy and security.
